In <strnlghtCo5wIo.1MA@netcom.com> strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:

>In article <1994Apr12.082914.16696@ttinews.tti.com>,
>Bob Smart <bsmart@bsmart.tti.com> wrote:

>>What judge?  What court order?  Nothing in the Clipper Initiative requires either
>>of those when seeking disclosure of keys.  I don't know how that will strike the
>>good citizens of Peoria, but I agree it's a pretty glaring omission...by the
>>sponsors of the initiative.  Respect for the courts is irrelevant here, since the
>>courts have no role in authorizing the release of escrowed keys.

>False. Read the NIST package on Clipper. State and Local authorities must
>have a wiretap court order, they must certify they do and cite it with their
>key request, and copies of the certification go to the Justice Department
>and both escrow agences for auditing.

Copies of the certification going to the Justice Department is new.  I
suppose, if the certification has the name and address of the judge, and
the escrow agencies are required to check the certification before giving
the key, that would make it almost respectable.

